  <!-- ════════ CAUTIONS — required content (rule #4), loud not buried ════════ -->
  <section class="dp-section dp-cautions" id="cautions">
    <p class="dp-eyebrow">Cautions</p>
    <h2>Read these before you lean on any of this</h2>
    <div class="dp-prose" style="max-width:none;">
      <p>This is where it&rsquo;s easy to get complacent &mdash; a personal forward projection can feel more certain than it is. These cautions are deliberately blunt.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="dp-caution-grid">
      <div class="dp-caution">
        <h3>The channel is a rising trend &mdash; waiting for the perfect entry can mean never entering.</h3>
        <p>Because the whole channel rises over time, holding out for an ideal low can backfire: price may simply keep climbing without giving you the entry you waited for. The cost of waiting is real, and it&rsquo;s why, on a long horizon, getting in tends to beat timing it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dp-caution">
        <h3>Price can move sideways for a long time.</h3>
        <p>&ldquo;High in the channel&rdquo; doesn&rsquo;t mean a drop is coming. Price can drift sideways for an extended stretch and then rise again. The upper-channel hedge looks smart in a backtest precisely because reversion eventually happened &mdash; there&rsquo;s no promise it happens on your timeline.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dp-caution">
        <h3>Bitcoin could break from the Power Law entirely.</h3>
        <p>To the upside or the downside. If it does, the tactics on this page are moot and you&rsquo;re on your own. The Power Law is a strong thesis worth taking seriously &mdash; but it&rsquo;s a thesis, not a law to lean on like dogma.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dp-caution dp-caution-blindspot">
        <h3>The math models a holder who never capitulates.</h3>
        <p>The backtest assumes you never sell in fear. A real person who deploys a lump and watches a 30% drawdown may sell and leave entirely. If that&rsquo;s a risk for you, laddering or a hybrid is staying-power insurance &mdash; a small expected cost for steadiness the numbers can&rsquo;t see. It&rsquo;s the honest reason to spread even when the channel says deploy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ COMMITMENT BACKSTOP ════════ -->
  <section class="dp-section dp-wide">
    <p class="dp-eyebrow">The commitment backstop</p>
    <h2>Given long enough, entries have historically recovered</h2>
    <div class="dp-prose" style="max-width:none;">
      <p>Three things compound into your eventual stack: <em>where</em> in the channel you bought, the <em>lump-vs-ladder-vs-hybrid</em> choice, and <em>patience</em> over a long horizon. They add up together &mdash; a long hold doesn&rsquo;t erase the edge from buying low in the channel, it builds on it. That said, the horizon does the heaviest lifting: over a <em>long</em> enough hold even a poorly-positioned entry has recovered. A multi-year tendency, not a promise &mdash; over short horizons entries have frequently sat underwater (including now &mdash; price has been below the Power Law trend about 58% of the time, above it about 42%). Mean value-multiple if you&rsquo;d deployed at each entry position the given number of years ago and <strong>held to today</strong> &mdash; computed live from the current price:</p>
    </div>
    <p class="dp-table-caption"><strong>Deployed N years ago and held to today</strong> &mdash; measured against <em>today&rsquo;s</em> price (what you&rsquo;d have now). This is a different question from the calculator table above, which holds each entry N years and measures against <em>its own price N years later</em> &mdash; so the 8-year cells differ, and both are honest.</p>
    <div class="dp-table-wrap">
      <table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Entry position</th><th>2&nbsp;yr</th><th>4&nbsp;yr</th><th>6&nbsp;yr</th><th>8&nbsp;yr</th></tr></thead>
