  <div class="dp-attribution">
    <span class="dp-attribution-label">Channel framework &amp; coefficients</span>
    The Power Law channel &mdash; floor at 0.42&times; trend, upper band at 3&times; trend &mdash; was developed by <a href="https://www.porkopolis.io/thechart/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Matthew Me&zcaron;inskis</strong></a> at Porkopolis Economics. Coefficients used: <code>a = 1.6&times;10<sup>&minus;17</sup></code>, <code>b = 5.77</code>. See <a href="/the-power-law#channel">The Channel</a> for the full case and attribution.
  </div>

  <div class="dp-method">
    <div class="dp-method-label">Methodology</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Channel position is the log-space location between floor and ceiling: <code>(ln(price/trend) &minus; ln 0.42) / (ln 3.0 &minus; ln 0.42)</code> &mdash; 0 at the floor, 1 at the upper band.</li>
      <li><strong>Entry is today.</strong> This page is anchored to now: the only variables are <em>how</em> you deploy (lump / ladder / hybrid) and how long you hold. Entry-position / &ldquo;when&rdquo; exploration &mdash; deploying high, low, or waiting &mdash; lives on the timing page, reached via the position-aware link above.</li>
      <li><strong>Retrospective table &mdash; &ldquo;held N years&rdquo;:</strong> takes the historical entries whose channel position is within &plusmn;0.07 of today&rsquo;s (a position at/below the floor folds into the floor), <strong>post-2014</strong>, and reports the <em>median</em> multiple of each strategy, each entry valued <em>N years after its own entry date</em>. Each column draws on the entries old enough for that hold, so the long-hold columns rest on fewer, older entries &mdash; the climb left-to-right is the patience lesson. The expandable <em>&ldquo;show all entries&rdquo;</em> view lists every entry behind the medians, with blank cells where an entry is too recent for that hold.</li>
      <li><strong>Two conventions, stated on each table.</strong> The calculator table measures against each entry&rsquo;s <em>own price N years later</em> (captures the cycle peak inside the window); the commitment-backstop table measures against <em>today&rsquo;s</em> price (&ldquo;held to today&rdquo;). They answer different questions and so show different eight-year numbers &mdash; both honest.</li>
      <li><strong>Early-era cut:</strong> the retrospective table excludes Bitcoin&rsquo;s pre-2014 curiosity era (2009&ndash;2012 traded as a sub-$15 curiosity whose returns no buyer today could replicate) &mdash; marked, never silently dropped. The today-anchored backstop needs no cut: anchoring exits to today already excludes those ancient cycle-peak exits.</li>
      <li><strong>Projection</strong> deploys today and extends two Power Law paths &mdash; reversion-to-trend and stay-on-trajectory &mdash; as a range per strategy and hold. Both are extrapolations of an empirical regularity, <em>not forecasts</em>.</li>
      <li>Lump deploys the full sum at once; ladder spreads it equally over the chosen duration; hybrid deploys a chosen share now and ladders the rest. Value is BTC accumulated &times; price along the path; multiples are amount-invariant, the dollar figures just scale with the sum.</li>
      <li>Commitment backstop: <strong>today-anchored</strong>. For each hold length N, entries deployed ~N years ago (a ~1.8-year window centred N years before today) are bucketed by channel position and valued at <strong>today&rsquo;s live price &divide; entry price</strong>. Recomputes live as the price moves.</li>
      <li id="dpMethodWindow">Computed live from the current <code>PL_DATA</code> window.</li>
      <li>Today&rsquo;s channel position is computed at load from the latest sample and the live spot (CoinGecko, via the shared fetch) &mdash; never baked in.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

